<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-04T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-04T00:00:00-05:00" n="214" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d214">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/6–448: Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Cabot</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-04">June 4,
                                1948</date>.<lb/>[Received June 3—10:50 p. m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1250. After several unheeded warnings Shanghai municipal authorities have
                            suspended local Soviet-owned Chinese morning daily tabloid <hi rend="italic">Shi Tai Jih Pao</hi>, 8000 circulation, for publishing
                            anti-Government propaganda. Official indictment is based on Article
                            21–29 of publication law charging attempt “to disrupt peace and order,
                            to disturb Government economic measures, to instigate students’ and
                            laborers’ riots and to spread rumors”.</p>
                        <p>Sent Department 1250, repeated Nanking 1006.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Cabot</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>